<h1><a href="duplicate-vs-save-as">Lion's "Duplicate" vs. the "Save as" of Yesteryear</a></h1>

<p>I've been using Mac OS X 10.7 Lion for almost a year now<sup>1</sup> and I am <em>still</em> fumbling with the dubious shift from the tried and true "Save as..." to the questionable "Duplicate". </p>

<p>Is it just me? Seriously. I'm okay with it if it is. It wouldn't be the first time that I disagreed with a fundamental change in the way things have been done for decades<sup>2</sup>. After all, it's human nature to fear change, right? Still, I just don't understand why Apple took away the straightforward, one-step process of clicking "Save as" and replaced it with:</p>

<ol>
<li>Click "Duplicate"</li>
<li>Click "Save"</li>
<li>Find and close original document window</li>
</ol>
<p>Now that, my friends, is efficiency.</p>

<hr>
<ol>
<li>Mac OS X 10.7 Lion was released "via the Mac App Store on July 20, 2011," says <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mac_OS_X_Lion">Wikipedia</a>. And yes, I was aboard that train on day 1.</li>
<li>Reverse scrolling. Need I say more? As it turns out, I thought I'd give it a try. And what do you know... I like it.</li>
</ol>

