<h1><a href="writeroom-for-cheap">WriteRoom: $2 well spent</a></h1>

<p><a href="http://www.hogbaysoftware.com/products/writeroom">WriteRoom</a>, the minimalist, distraction-free writing environment is $2 on the <a href="http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/writeroom/id417967324?mt=12">Mac App Store</a> today (2012-05-29).</p>

<p>In this increasingly crowded arena, I've tried 'em all: <a href="http://www.iawriter.com/">IA Writer</a>, <a href="http://bywordapp.com/">Byword</a>, <a href="http://mouapp.com/">Mou</a>, etc... While they've all got their strengths (along with plenty of weaknesses), WriteRoom shines in one important area: its writing window is very customizable... well no, not really. But it's more customizable than its competitors anyway. IA Writer, for example, offers no options for tweaking the editor. None. It is the epitome of the "<em>just fucking write, you dolt</em>" style of app. And I get that. Really. At the end if the day, it's the words on the page that matter, not finding the perfect shade of background gray that will be most conducive to writing a Pulitzer-quality blog post about distraction free writing environments. That said, nerds will be nerds and nerds need to tweak. WriteRoom, I think, provides just enough tweakablity without completely going down the nerd hole.</p>

<p>If WriteRoom has one flaw, it's the (glaringly painful) omission of Markdown awareness. Most other editors in this category offer some level of Markdown support. In Byword, typing <code># My Title</code> changes that line to bold, indicating that it's a heading. <code>1. First item</code> is recognized as the first entry in a numbered list. Hitting enter after that, automatically adds the obvious next line: <code>2.</code>...</p>

<p>Here's the thing though: Markdown was created to be editor agnostic. <em>Got a plain text editor? Okay, you're ready to rock Markdown.</em> So maybe Markdown awareness in a distraction free writing environment is... well, a distraction.</p>

<p>Anyway, for now, WriteRoom is my BFF. And for $2, it should be yours too. Get it while it's hot!</p>

<p><a href="http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/writeroom/id417967324?mt=12">WriteRoom for $2 on the Mac App Store &rarr;</a></p>

<footer><p>Posted on May 29, 2012 at 11:23 AM</p></footer></article><article>
<h1><a href="scandalous">Scandalous!</a></h1>

<p>I really, <strong>really</strong>, <strong>REALLY</strong> want to know what happened to cause <a href="http://daringfireball.net/colophon/">John Gruber</a> to break up with <a href="http://5by5.tv/people/dan-benjamin">Dan Benjamin</a>. They had such chemistry.</p>

<p>Some brief history: John did a podcast on Ben's network, <a href="http://5by5.tv/">5by5</a>, called <a href="http://5by5.tv/talkshow">The Talk Show</a>. It was about Mac and tech news mostly, but they left in plenty of time for general bullshitting. It was good. I was a super-fan. Then one day, The Talk Show was no more. </p>

<p>Well not exactly. John took his (<em>was it his to take?</em>) show, title and all, to the <a href="http://muleradio.net/thetalkshow/">Mule Radio Syndicate</a>. Only during his <a href="http://muleradio.net/thetalkshow/2/">second episode</a> on Mule (with the fabulous <a href="http://lonelysandwich.com/">Lonely Sandwich</a>, A.K.A. <a href="http://adamlisagor.com/">Adam Lisagor</a> of <a href="http://sandwichvideo.com/">Sandwich Video</a>) did he address the elephant in the room... <em>errr</em>... podcast. And even then, details were sparse. Although, John did elude to some kind of business decision of Ben's that he just wasn't onboard with.</p>

<p>Dan attempted to be more official with the news by putting out a <a href="http://5by5.tv/specials/6">special episode</a> on 5by5 to address the situation. It was fluff though; no real details anywhere to be found. Still, I listened with rapt attention.</p>

<p>And that's all we know. Or at least that's all I know. I feel like a child of a messy divorce... no, not messy; confusing. It's like my parents, who I've always thought got on splendidly, one day announced that they're splitting up. Publicly, theirs was a model relationship. Behind closed doors, however, things were apparently very different.</p>

<p>(Clearly, I've a few issues of my own to work out here.)</p>

